{
  "texts": [
    "The cause of this is suggested by the third panel, which shows the noise correlation factor:C n = σ rand /σ uncorr.",
    "(A.1)The correlation factor can be seen to increase in regions of the image where there is considerable background contamination from, for example, residual reflections from bright stars.A170, page 36 of 54 A170, page 37 of 54 As mentioned in Sect. 3.2, the KiDS data are calibrated to Gaia stars at the J2000 epoch.",
    "In practice, this means that the positions of stars used to calibrate KiDS have been shifted (using their observed positions and estimated proper motions) back to where they would have been in the year 2000.",
    "Crucially, though, this does not just have a random effect per star: as the Solar System moves through the Milky Way, an additional coherent shift is imprinted on the stellar distribution.",
    "The purpose of calibrating to J2000 epoch stellar positions is to remove this coherent drift."
  ]
}